1
00:00:02,603 --> 00:00:04,047
<i>- Previously on</i> Grey's
Anatomy: - I slept with Izzie.

2
00:00:04,071 --> 00:00:06,088
George told me. Everything.

3
00:00:06,190 --> 00:00:08,957
You named me Ava and
I was more me as Ava

4
00:00:09,059 --> 00:00:10,659
than I'll ever be as Rebecca.

5
00:00:10,727 --> 00:00:12,794
Dr. Hahn. I was
pleasantly surprised

6
00:00:12,896 --> 00:00:14,579
to hear you were
joining us today.

7
00:00:14,681 --> 00:00:17,098
You remind me of myself
when I was an intern.

8
00:00:17,200 --> 00:00:20,068
Focused, intense. Cold.

9
00:00:20,170 --> 00:00:22,820
- My mother's dead, isn't she?
- Yes.

10
00:00:22,923 --> 00:00:25,257
Let's do this once. I'm
fine. She's cremated.

11
00:00:25,359 --> 00:00:26,725
I picked out a beautiful urn,

12
00:00:26,827 --> 00:00:28,710
she's hanging out in
the back of my closet.

13
00:00:28,812 --> 00:00:33,265
Any more questions about my dead
mother or can we get back to work?

14
00:00:37,354 --> 00:00:40,706
Pick me. Choose me. Love me.

15
00:00:42,759 --> 00:00:44,927
You're the love of my
life. I can't leave you.

16
00:00:45,029 --> 00:00:47,779
But you're
constantly leaving me.

17
00:00:47,881 --> 00:00:50,966
Imagine my disappointment
when I wake up after five years

18
00:00:51,068 --> 00:00:53,902
and discover that you're
no more than ordinary!

19
00:00:58,158 --> 00:01:02,127
<i>There's a reason surgeons
learn to wield scalpels.</i>

20
00:01:02,229 --> 00:01:06,465
<i>We like to pretend we're
hard, cold scientists.</i>

21
00:01:06,567 --> 00:01:09,384
<i>We like to pretend
we're fearless.</i>

22
00:01:10,453 --> 00:01:16,408
Pick me. Choose me. Love me.

23
00:01:16,510 --> 00:01:20,996
<i>But the truth is we become surgeons
because somewhere, deep down,</i>

24
00:01:21,098 --> 00:01:25,099
<i>we think we can cut
away that which haunts us.</i>

25
00:01:27,604 --> 00:01:30,572
- What are you guys doing up?
- Couldn't sleep.

26
00:01:30,674 --> 00:01:32,174
<i>Weakness.</i>

27
00:01:32,276 --> 00:01:34,008
<i>Frailty.</i>

28
00:01:34,110 --> 00:01:35,810
<i>Death.</i>

29
00:01:46,490 --> 00:01:48,022
What is that?

30
00:01:50,010 --> 00:01:51,893
My mother.

31
00:01:52,746 --> 00:01:54,930
Happy freaking Halloween.

32
00:02:04,125 --> 00:02:05,690
Yang.

33
00:02:05,792 --> 00:02:07,926
You're moving out
of Burke's place?

34
00:02:08,028 --> 00:02:09,794
Yes, sir.

35
00:02:10,597 --> 00:02:12,781
My wife has filed for divorce.

36
00:02:13,851 --> 00:02:15,534
I'm very sorry, sir.

37
00:02:15,636 --> 00:02:17,669
At any rate, I need
a place to live.

38
00:02:17,771 --> 00:02:20,421
And Burke's place,
I was there once.

39
00:02:20,523 --> 00:02:22,357
I suppose actually
it's your place now.

40
00:02:22,459 --> 00:02:24,893
No. It's still Burke's place.

41
00:02:28,364 --> 00:02:29,798
Now, it's yours.

42
00:02:38,992 --> 00:02:40,775
What are we looking at?

43
00:02:40,877 --> 00:02:44,346
Meredith put her mom in a
baggie and brought her to work.

44
00:02:44,448 --> 00:02:47,365
I had to get her out of my
closet. She was haunting me.

45
00:02:47,467 --> 00:02:49,618
And now she's haunting us all.

46
00:02:49,736 --> 00:02:52,571
- I'm putting her to rest.
- Meredith is cleansing.

47
00:02:52,656 --> 00:02:55,474
In tribal culture when one
wants to cleanse the past,

48
00:02:55,576 --> 00:02:58,459
one cuts off all of one's
hair and buries it in the earth.

49
00:02:58,561 --> 00:03:00,678
You might try that too.

50
00:03:01,598 --> 00:03:04,082
OK. Listen up.
Today's a holiday,

51
00:03:04,167 --> 00:03:05,978
which means the
pit will be overrun.

52
00:03:06,002 --> 00:03:08,162
You've got the usual
drunken stupidity.

53
00:03:08,188 --> 00:03:10,233
And then you've
got Seattle's annual

54
00:03:10,257 --> 00:03:12,468
chainsaw pumpkin
carving contest.

55
00:03:12,492 --> 00:03:14,559
- I love this city.
- Stay on your toes,

56
00:03:14,661 --> 00:03:15,978
stay on top of your interns, OK?

57
00:03:16,080 --> 00:03:18,029
So we should
round before the pit?

58
00:03:18,131 --> 00:03:20,948
Direct your questions
to Dr. Bailey, Stevens.

59
00:03:21,050 --> 00:03:24,052
Oh, we're directing our
questions to Dr. Bailey?

60
00:03:24,154 --> 00:03:25,637
Oh, not you. Just Stevens.

61
00:03:25,739 --> 00:03:28,923
Why is Stevens directing
her questions to Dr. Bailey?

62
00:03:29,026 --> 00:03:31,994
Because she's been
sleeping with my husband.

63
00:03:37,434 --> 00:03:39,651
Alrighty, then. Have a good day.

64
00:03:49,329 --> 00:03:53,147
OK, this is even more disturbing
than your bag full of mommy.

65
00:03:53,249 --> 00:03:55,450
His medication was
due half an hour ago.

66
00:03:55,552 --> 00:03:58,570
The man is living in the
hospital while he waits on a heart.

67
00:03:58,672 --> 00:04:01,622
Erin, honey, I'm
thinking it's kind of hard

68
00:04:01,725 --> 00:04:05,026
for anyone to take you
seriously in your mouse costume.

69
00:04:05,128 --> 00:04:07,779
See, I work with
five-year-olds, Dad.

70
00:04:07,881 --> 00:04:10,949
My costume is
appropriate. Hers is not.

71
00:04:11,051 --> 00:04:15,003
Look, I'm just saying if you have
time for Halloween costumes,

72
00:04:15,105 --> 00:04:18,272
you probably have time to
provide my father with basic care.

73
00:04:18,375 --> 00:04:22,427
Hi. I'm Dr. O'Malley. I will take
care of your father right away.

74
00:04:22,529 --> 00:04:24,429
Thank you.

75
00:04:24,531 --> 00:04:26,812
You should always make
sure they have their meds

76
00:04:26,900 --> 00:04:28,578
before you do anything else.

77
00:04:28,602 --> 00:04:30,669
- There you go.
- Thanks.

78
00:04:30,771 --> 00:04:33,105
- I like your costume.
- Oh.

79
00:04:33,207 --> 00:04:34,573
Well, Dr. Yang said that...

80
00:04:34,674 --> 00:04:37,208
Dr. Yang is screwing with you.

81
00:04:39,179 --> 00:04:42,197
Oh! I knew it.

82
00:04:43,450 --> 00:04:45,800
- Are you the doctor?
- Oh. I am.

83
00:04:45,902 --> 00:04:49,370
Good. That's... That's good.

84
00:04:50,073 --> 00:04:51,639
Is your leg hurting you?

85
00:04:51,741 --> 00:04:54,609
It's not the leg, it's the foot.

86
00:04:54,711 --> 00:04:59,464
And it's not hurting so
much as it's not mine.

87
00:04:59,566 --> 00:05:01,811
Something happened.
I can't explain it,

88
00:05:01,835 --> 00:05:04,535
but this foot does
not belong to me.

89
00:05:04,637 --> 00:05:06,888
It's...

90
00:05:06,990 --> 00:05:11,209
It... It... Well, it feels
like it's a corpse foot.

91
00:05:11,311 --> 00:05:13,628
Did you lose feeling
in the foot? Is it numb?

92
00:05:13,730 --> 00:05:16,698
No, it's not numb. It's just...

93
00:05:16,800 --> 00:05:18,015
It's not mine.

94
00:05:18,117 --> 00:05:20,635
Please. I'm not crazy.

95
00:05:20,737 --> 00:05:22,971
I work in a bank.
I'm not crazy. Please.

96
00:05:23,073 --> 00:05:24,538
I just... I need a surgeon.

97
00:05:24,641 --> 00:05:28,810
I need you to get me a
surgeon who will remove it.

98
00:05:28,912 --> 00:05:30,912
A surgeon who will
remove your foot?

99
00:05:31,014 --> 00:05:36,968
A surgeon who will amputate
your seemingly healthy foot?

100
00:05:43,059 --> 00:05:44,542
- Oh!
- Whoa!

101
00:05:47,547 --> 00:05:49,548
- What is that?
- It's charts.

102
00:05:49,650 --> 00:05:51,277
- Meredith?
- It's my mom.

103
00:05:51,301 --> 00:05:52,861
- What?
- Had her in the cubby

104
00:05:52,886 --> 00:05:54,252
and she was freaking people out

105
00:05:54,354 --> 00:05:56,032
so I was gonna
put her in the car.

106
00:05:56,056 --> 00:05:58,773
Think that's disrespectful?
To leave her in the car?

107
00:05:58,875 --> 00:06:00,875
- Just a little...
- It's not that strange.

108
00:06:00,927 --> 00:06:02,911
- Well...
- I'm trying to figure out

109
00:06:03,013 --> 00:06:04,190
how to put her to rest.

110
00:06:04,214 --> 00:06:06,374
I can't shove her in
my closet anymore.

111
00:06:06,466 --> 00:06:07,693
I have to deal with her.

112
00:06:07,717 --> 00:06:11,786
- Well...
- And this is me... trying to evolve.

113
00:06:11,888 --> 00:06:15,307
I'm trying here.
So, cubby or car?

114
00:06:15,409 --> 00:06:18,743
You're asking me if I think you
should put your mom's ashes

115
00:06:18,845 --> 00:06:20,478
in your cubby or your car? OK.

116
00:06:20,581 --> 00:06:22,714
And you don't think
that's very, very strange?

117
00:06:22,816 --> 00:06:25,100
Are those really
your mom's ashes?

118
00:06:25,202 --> 00:06:27,602
It's strange,
right? It's strange.

119
00:06:27,704 --> 00:06:31,505
- Are you lost?
- No. My mom works
in the cafeteria.

120
00:06:31,607 --> 00:06:34,075
She said I could come up
here and look for Dr. Sloan?

121
00:06:34,177 --> 00:06:35,438
Do you know him?

122
00:06:35,462 --> 00:06:37,178
Um... can you take care of him?

123
00:06:37,280 --> 00:06:40,832
Yeah. Can you take care of her?

124
00:06:46,673 --> 00:06:49,007
Good morning.

125
00:06:49,109 --> 00:06:51,910
- Don't do that. Don't smile at me.
- Don't smile at her.

126
00:06:52,012 --> 00:06:54,062
- Don't smile at me either.
- We're on to you.

127
00:06:54,164 --> 00:06:56,748
- We've compared notes.
- Compared notes. Really?

128
00:06:56,850 --> 00:07:00,502
Mm-hmm. Compared notes,
pick-up lines, techniques.

129
00:07:00,620 --> 00:07:02,971
- Techniques?
- Identical.

130
00:07:03,072 --> 00:07:05,673
- Identical?
- We've formed a club.

131
00:07:05,775 --> 00:07:08,342
"Nurses United
Against Mark Sloan."

132
00:07:09,797 --> 00:07:13,915
Are there any,
uh... club activities?

133
00:07:18,187 --> 00:07:20,889
Oh, man. You would not
believe what just happened to me.

134
00:07:20,991 --> 00:07:23,958
- There's a... kid looking for you.
- What?

135
00:07:25,261 --> 00:07:28,479
- Daddy?
- What?

136
00:07:30,851 --> 00:07:33,751
- Nicely done.
- Thanks.

137
00:07:33,853 --> 00:07:36,771
- I'll be getting
you back for that.
- Looking forward to it.

138
00:07:36,873 --> 00:07:39,658
You're not my father.

139
00:07:39,760 --> 00:07:42,093
But I am hoping you'll
build me some ears.

140
00:07:43,997 --> 00:07:47,265
Dr. Karev? Request
for you. Curtain three.

141
00:07:47,367 --> 00:07:50,135
Dr. Karev? I'm feeling a
little under the weather.

142
00:07:50,236 --> 00:07:53,004
And rather than risk
spreading germs to the patients,

143
00:07:53,106 --> 00:07:54,338
I thought I'd head home.

144
00:07:54,440 --> 00:07:56,786
Do you want to be a surgeon
or do you want to go to bed?

145
00:07:56,810 --> 00:07:58,788
One or the other.
Surgeons stand up

146
00:07:58,812 --> 00:08:00,589
through ten, 12,
15-hour surgeries.

147
00:08:00,613 --> 00:08:03,848
Without food. Without bathroom
breaks. Without complaints.

148
00:08:03,950 --> 00:08:07,318
Surgeons do not go home because
we have a tickle in our throat.

149
00:08:09,088 --> 00:08:10,872
Not a tickle in my
throat as much as...

150
00:08:10,974 --> 00:08:14,041
- Make yourself busy, Norman.
- Right.

151
00:08:20,317 --> 00:08:23,818
All the moms in my town,
they all dress up for Halloween.

152
00:08:23,920 --> 00:08:27,021
So I was thinking,
what would I want to be?

153
00:08:27,124 --> 00:08:29,168
If I had to dress
up, what would I...?

154
00:08:29,192 --> 00:08:32,777
And the only thing I
could come up with,

155
00:08:32,880 --> 00:08:37,048
the only thing that I
wanted to be... was Ava.

156
00:08:37,150 --> 00:08:41,452
<i>♪ But I need your
little shining light ♪</i>

157
00:08:47,277 --> 00:08:52,713
<i>♪ You promised the world
Opened up your door ♪</i>

158
00:08:54,701 --> 00:08:59,604
<i>♪ And the words you fed
me left me wanting more ♪</i>

159
00:09:01,808 --> 00:09:03,541
You found him.

160
00:09:03,643 --> 00:09:06,878
You two know each other?
You know his parents?

161
00:09:06,980 --> 00:09:10,147
His mom works in the
cafeteria. What's all this?

162
00:09:10,250 --> 00:09:12,294
Letters from the
kids in my class.

163
00:09:12,318 --> 00:09:13,718
Letters to me.

164
00:09:13,820 --> 00:09:15,887
He has the internal
structure to hear.

165
00:09:15,989 --> 00:09:18,940
He just doesn't have the
canal or the external structure.

166
00:09:19,042 --> 00:09:21,492
So I thought if I came
in with my letters,

167
00:09:21,594 --> 00:09:24,829
Dr. Sloan might feel sorry for
me and do the surgery for free.

168
00:09:24,931 --> 00:09:27,131
Uh, look, I'd like to help.

169
00:09:27,233 --> 00:09:29,333
I would if I could, but
pro bono surgery...

170
00:09:29,419 --> 00:09:31,146
You should know
that on my way here

171
00:09:31,170 --> 00:09:33,672
three different people
thought I was in a costume.

172
00:09:33,774 --> 00:09:37,692
My head looks like a
permanent Halloween costume.

173
00:09:38,928 --> 00:09:42,480
- Just thought
you should know that.
- You're good.

174
00:09:42,582 --> 00:09:46,167
Pro bono surgery's not just
about me giving you my time.

175
00:09:46,269 --> 00:09:49,704
A surgery like this requires
OR time, an anesthesiologist,

176
00:09:49,806 --> 00:09:52,690
a general surgeon to remove
the cartilage from your ribs,

177
00:09:52,792 --> 00:09:57,846
- at least two surgical nurses.
- Couldn't you
ask them for help?

178
00:09:57,947 --> 00:10:00,865
I could. But I don't
have any social capital.

179
00:10:00,967 --> 00:10:04,602
The nurses hate me. They've
formed a club that's all about hating me.

180
00:10:04,704 --> 00:10:06,938
And the other doctors
don't owe me any favors

181
00:10:07,040 --> 00:10:09,557
because I've never
done any for them.

182
00:10:09,659 --> 00:10:12,660
I'm sorry. I wish I could help.

183
00:10:13,396 --> 00:10:15,813
I would if I could.

184
00:10:18,651 --> 00:10:20,318
I have social capital.

185
00:10:21,371 --> 00:10:23,088
Or, I don't. Nobody knows me,

186
00:10:23,189 --> 00:10:24,469
but they knew my mother.

187
00:10:24,508 --> 00:10:26,190
So maybe I can make this happen.

188
00:10:26,292 --> 00:10:30,278
Fine. Make it happen. You
manage that, I'm all yours.

189
00:10:32,115 --> 00:10:34,765
These people who
knew your mother...

190
00:10:34,868 --> 00:10:37,318
Do they know you brought
her to work in a baggie?

191
00:10:46,846 --> 00:10:50,247
Oh. You... You...

192
00:10:51,451 --> 00:10:54,251
You didn't come for me! You...

193
00:10:55,188 --> 00:10:56,854
You chickened out.

194
00:10:56,956 --> 00:11:00,858
When I... When I was
leaving. When I was...

195
00:11:00,960 --> 00:11:03,072
When I asked you to
give me a reason to stay,

196
00:11:03,096 --> 00:11:04,940
you chickened out. Which I get.

197
00:11:04,964 --> 00:11:07,364
I get that. It was a lot.

198
00:11:07,466 --> 00:11:09,779
It was scary. And I know
it can be kind of intense,

199
00:11:09,803 --> 00:11:13,137
but I thought-I thought... Oh.

200
00:11:13,239 --> 00:11:17,875
I thought after the
chickening out part, I thought...

201
00:11:17,977 --> 00:11:20,144
you would come for me.

202
00:11:22,232 --> 00:11:27,485
I came back for you. Which
basically makes me a beggar.

203
00:11:27,587 --> 00:11:30,188
I'm a beggar for Halloween.

204
00:11:30,290 --> 00:11:33,824
- And now you're mocking me.
- I'm not mocking you.

205
00:11:42,352 --> 00:11:44,852
We need to talk.

206
00:11:44,954 --> 00:11:46,554
We will.

207
00:11:48,658 --> 00:11:50,375
Body Dysmorphic Disorder?

208
00:11:50,476 --> 00:11:52,704
You can prescribe
some anti-anxiety meds,

209
00:11:52,728 --> 00:11:55,163
to try to lessen the
urgency he's feeling.

210
00:11:55,265 --> 00:11:57,999
The man is requesting
an amputation

211
00:11:58,101 --> 00:12:01,369
and the best you can come
up with is anti-anxiety meds?

212
00:12:02,005 --> 00:12:03,637
Dr. Bailey?

213
00:12:04,724 --> 00:12:06,891
- Chainsaw contest time?
- Yep.

214
00:12:08,227 --> 00:12:10,478
- Mr. Miller.
- Duquette Clinic.

215
00:12:10,580 --> 00:12:11,879
I have to get to the ER,

216
00:12:11,981 --> 00:12:14,715
but I'm going to write
you a prescription

217
00:12:14,817 --> 00:12:16,750
for some medication
I think may help you.

218
00:12:16,852 --> 00:12:19,387
Medication? I need...
I need a surgeon.

219
00:12:19,489 --> 00:12:22,724
A surgeon can take off
the foot. Get me a surgeon!

220
00:12:22,826 --> 00:12:25,426
I am a surgeon! And I
can tell you right now

221
00:12:25,529 --> 00:12:29,230
that you won't persuade me or any
other surgeon to do what you're asking.

222
00:12:29,332 --> 00:12:31,465
Please, try this medication.

223
00:12:33,636 --> 00:12:35,936
I have an earless boy.

224
00:12:36,940 --> 00:12:38,022
I'm sorry?

225
00:12:38,124 --> 00:12:41,141
Sloan has agreed to
build him ears pro bono.

226
00:12:41,244 --> 00:12:44,044
If you will donate the
OR and all the equipment.

227
00:12:44,146 --> 00:12:48,716
I'm sorry, my pro bono slate is full,
there are protocols to be followed,

228
00:12:48,818 --> 00:12:51,552
- all sorts of red tape...
- Trick or treat.

229
00:12:52,806 --> 00:12:55,807
Get it? He's trick
or treating. For ears.

230
00:12:57,193 --> 00:12:59,159
- Grey...
- You know, my mother...

231
00:12:59,262 --> 00:13:01,645
She was big on
pro bono surgeries.

232
00:13:06,436 --> 00:13:08,987
OR two is free at 6:00pm.

233
00:13:09,089 --> 00:13:10,905
Thank you.

234
00:13:15,612 --> 00:13:18,007
If you two need to talk
I could wait over there.

235
00:13:18,031 --> 00:13:20,748
Why? It's not like we
have any secrets anymore.

236
00:13:20,850 --> 00:13:22,517
Callie told everyone. Everyone.

237
00:13:22,618 --> 00:13:24,664
Yeah. It's going
to be a long day.

238
00:13:24,688 --> 00:13:28,873
Erin Shanley, 34, massive head trauma,
a brick came through her windshield.

239
00:13:28,975 --> 00:13:31,009
- GCS of three.
- Brick through her windshield?

240
00:13:31,111 --> 00:13:33,711
